description: From Late Latin ēns (“thing”), from esse (“to be”). See entity.

entries.meaning: (philosophy) An entity or being; an existing thing, as opposed to a quality or attribute.
examples: Forms sphered in fire with trembling light array'd, / Ens without weight, and substance without shade  […] .

entries.meaning: (chemistry, alchemy, now historical) Something supposed to condense within itself all the virtues and qualities of a substance from which it is extracted; an essence, an active principle.
examples: Here he states that there are five ‘active principles’ – the five Enses or entia – that influence our bodies and give rise to disease  […]
